			<section>
				<h2 class="section-title">Background</h2>
				<div class="content">
					<p>
						I am a Ph.D. student at the Center for Astrophysics, University of Southern Queensland, 
						where I study stellar evolution and asteroseismology. 
					</p>
					<div style="height: 10px;"></div>
					<p>
						My academic journey began with a Bachelor's degree in Electronics and Telecommunication 
						from the Army Institute of Technology, University of Pune, followed by a transition to astrophysics 
						due to my growing fascination with the subject. Although my Master's studies at the Australian National 
						University were interrupted, I continued to pursue astrophysics through a project on high-energy astrophysics 
						at the same institution. There, I explored the rotational evolution of accretion induced collapse 
						millisecond pulsars, using these stellar remnants to probe whether a hitherto unobserved population 
						of them could explain the Milky Way bulge gamma-ray excess. This research experience reinforced my interest 
						in computational stellar evolution and led me to my current research on delta Scuti stars.
					</p>
					<div style="height: 10px;"></div>
					<p>
						My current work is focussed on producing theoretical models for these stars to understand how 
						various physical and computational parameters influence their pulsation behaviour. 
						I use these stellar pulsation models to infer fundamental properties, like age, mass, 
						and metallicities, for observed delta Scuti stars.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>
